{"type":"message","id":"d95b8f59","parentId":"8a7d72b6","timestamp":"2026-05-08T14:26:22.788Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The regex on line 946 is:\n```\nb'([^\"\\'>,)]+)[\"\\']?\\', params_str):'\n```\n\nThis has `([\\^\"'>,)]+)` which is:\n- `(` - start capture\n- `[^\\\"'>,)]` - character class with `^` (negation), `\"`, `'`, `>`, `,`, `)`, `]` - but the `]` was expected to be the close of the character class!\n- Wait, looking at the hex: `5b` = `[`, `5e` = `^`, `22` = `\"`, `27` = `'`, `3e` = `>`, `2c` = `,`, `29` = `)`, `5d` = `]`\n\n\nSo the character class is actually `[^\\\"'>,)]` - it should be a negation with all those characters inside, and then `+` quantifier. But the closing `]` is at the end, which is correct for a character class.\n\nPython's error about mismatched parentheses doesn't make sense given this structure. I'm wondering if Python is interpreting something differently than what I'm reading from the hex dump - maybe the escape sequences or quotes are being parsed in an unexpected way.\n\nLooking more closely at the escape sequences: `\\'` in a Python bytes literal is just a single quote character, not an escape. The raw bytes show `5c 27` which is backslash followed by quote, but within a bytes literal `b'...'`, that sequence would actually terminate the string early since `\\'` isn't a recognized escape in bytes.\n\nExamining the hex more carefully, I see the pattern `5c 27` (backslash-quote) appears multiple times, which suggests the string might actually be: `([\\^\"'>,)]+` - the backslash before the second quote would escape it, allowing the character class to contain a literal quote. But that still doesn't align with what Python is reporting about mismatched parentheses.\n\nLet me trace through the full hex sequence `5b5e22273e2c295d` to understand what character class this actually represents and why the parser is complaining about unmatched `]` versus `)`. I'm decoding the byte sequence character by character: `[^\\\"'>,)]` forms a character class that matches anything except quote, apostrophe, greater than, comma, and closing parenthesis. The `+` quantifier means one or more of these characters, and the trailing `?` makes the quote wrapper optional. This explains the structure of the regex pattern, though I'm still uncertain about what comes after the second quote mark based on the hex values.\n\nLooking at the error message more carefully, it's reporting that a closing parenthesis `)` doesn't match an opening parenthesis `(`, which suggests the character class might not be properly closed. In PCRE regex, character classes use `[...]` syntax, but Python's `re` module might be interpreting this differently—possibly as a nested group instead. The error at column 36 points to the `)` inside what should be the character class, indicating Python thinks that parenthesis is trying to close something that wasn't properly opened with a matching `(`.\n\nThe character class `[^\\\"'>,)]` should theoretically work—it negates the set containing quote, apostrophe, greater than, comma, and closing parenthesis. But the error suggests something else is going wrong with how Python is parsing the regex pattern itself, particularly around line 946 where the actual syntax error occurs. I need to reconsider what the file actually contains. Let me use a Python script to directly read and display line 946 to see the exact raw bytes without any interpretation issues.\n","thinkingSignature":"12a9032cc928f8572174838824dae4e44137ab1388a906e9199f4423af5d5a48"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_8a3o0r3o9qxg_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 << 'PYEOF'\nwith open('/home/apinan/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/universal_bridge.py', 'rb') as f:\n    data = f.read()\n\nlines = data.split(b'\\n')\nline_946 = lines[945]  # 0-indexed\n\n# Find the problematic regex\nimport re\nm = re.search(rb're\\.finditer\\((.+?)\\, params_str\\)', line_946)\nif m:\n    regex_bytes = m.g